at contexts girls behave violently, and look at the links between girls' violence and the broader issues of the social construction and social control of adolescent femininities. With diverse essays representing different geographical and disciplinary perspectives, this book offers, at times, contradictory evidence and conflicting views. However, common concerns are clear and the reader is rewarded with a rich exploration of the struggles of girls and young women to take control of their lives in material and ideological conditions that continue to restrict their options and opportunities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFemale juvenile delinquentsvCross-cultural studies. 0aFemale offendersvCross-cultural studies. 0aTeenage girlsxPsychology. 4aCriminology : Criminology. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aPsychology : Adolescent Studies. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAlder, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlder, Christine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aArtz, Sibylle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatacharya, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurman, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodfrey, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Jody, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearce, Jenny J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaffner, Laurie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhite, Norman A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWorrall, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/